00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:23.130 --> 00:00:26.690 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon, and welcome to
the African and Middle East Division

00:00:26.690 --> 00:00:28.570
of the Library of Congress.

00:00:28.570 --> 00:00:31.470
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb, Chief of
the Division, and I'm very happy

00:00:31.470 --> 00:00:36.510
to see you all here for a
very special presentation

00:00:36.510 --> 00:00:41.650 position:56%
with Dr. Rana Al Kadi, who will talk
to us about a fascinating subject

00:00:41.650 --> 00:00:46.620
that we have not often
addressed in our lecture series,

00:00:46.620 --> 00:00:50.200
and that is Islamic architecture.

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:54.770
This presentation is co-sponsored
with the Middle East Institute,

00:00:54.770 --> 00:01:00.760
and I would like to thank
more particularly Kate Seely,

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:04.770
the Senior Vice President of
the Institute for suggesting

00:01:04.770 --> 00:01:07.330
that the Library of Congress
would be the ideal setting

00:01:07.330 --> 00:01:08.630
for this lecture.

00:01:08.630 --> 00:01:12.910
I was the one to thank Diedre,
who is here, and I've just met,

00:01:12.910 --> 00:01:16.230
from the Middle East
Institute, there she is,

00:01:16.230 --> 00:01:21.730
and who has organized this
program from this side

00:01:21.730 --> 00:01:23.730
of the Middle East Institute.

00:01:23.730 --> 00:01:26.330
But before we introduce
our speaker today,

00:01:26.330 --> 00:01:31.450
I would like to make my usual
commercial about our division here.

00:01:31.450 --> 00:01:36.250
As many of you know, our division
is made up of three sections.

00:01:36.250 --> 00:01:41.230
The African, the Hebraic,
and the [inaudible] sections,

00:01:41.230 --> 00:01:47.340
and we cover over-we're responsible
at least-for over 78 countries

00:01:47.340 --> 00:01:53.440
in the region including in the
whole of Africa, Central Asia,

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:56.540
the Caucuses, and beyond.

00:01:56.540 --> 00:02:05.870
And we invite people
to use our collections,

00:02:05.870 --> 00:02:11.320
so this is a reading room,
and it is in this reading room

00:02:11.320 --> 00:02:13.590
that people will come
and do research.

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:15.130
We're not a lending library.

00:02:15.130 --> 00:02:19.030
We're not like the public
libraries that lend out books.

00:02:19.030 --> 00:02:20.830
We collect materials.

00:02:20.830 --> 00:02:22.820
The whole library collects
materials from the whole world,

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:25.470
in all languages, in all scripts.

00:02:25.470 --> 00:02:28.460
In fact, this division
collects materials

00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:31.780
in the vernacular-in other
words, if you're doing research

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:38.330
on Islamic architecture, if the
materials are in Arabic or Turkish

00:02:38.330 --> 00:02:42.560
or in Persian, those
materials would be here.

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:49.780
But if the materials that you want
are in English, French, German,

00:02:49.780 --> 00:02:53.360
or Italian, or whatever, they're
part of the general collection.

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:58.410
So we are focused on languages,
rather than on national,

00:02:58.410 --> 00:03:01.650
political entities as such.

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:05.090
We're very active in acquiring
and developing our collections.

00:03:05.090 --> 00:03:08.010
We're active in serving
our collections.

00:03:08.010 --> 00:03:13.680
We also, this place,
we brief people.

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:19.170
We have groups that
come, often organized

00:03:19.170 --> 00:03:25.680 position:56%
by different organizations, or by
the International Visitor's Program,

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:31.580
of the State Department, so we
do a great deal of interacting

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:35.100
with people from our regions.

00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:41.650
We have had exhibits, major
exhibits, in the past few years.

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:45.810
And we hope to have more of them.

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:51.190
And we also invite scholars
and experts who have researched

00:03:51.190 --> 00:03:54.950
and done work in our
areas of responsibility,

00:03:54.950 --> 00:03:59.350
to share with us their
insights, and their findings.

00:03:59.350 --> 00:04:02.360
So that all of us attending
and participating

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:06.750
in the programs leave
enriched with new information

00:04:06.750 --> 00:04:09.640
and a better understanding
of the cultures

00:04:09.640 --> 00:04:13.550
and societies whose
publications we collect.

00:04:13.550 --> 00:04:17.550
A case in point, of course,
is the scholar we have today.

00:04:17.550 --> 00:04:22.750
Dr. Al Kadi is from Saudi
Arabia, and a native of Medina.

00:04:22.750 --> 00:04:24.050
And therefore, well located

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:29.540
to discuss this important
subject, Islamic architecture.

00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:31.690
However, there is a twist here.

00:04:31.690 --> 00:04:37.090 position:56%
Her research on Islamic architecture
has focused on the western part

00:04:37.090 --> 00:04:40.380
of the Muslim world,
on North Africa, Spain,

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:41.960
rather than on the eastern part.

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:44.040
At least this is my understanding.

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:45.790
Perhaps she will correct me.

00:04:45.790 --> 00:04:51.720
And I hope that she
will tell us what it was

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:54.860
that drew her in that direction.

00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:58.690
But now, for a fuller
introduction of Dr. Al Kadi,

00:04:58.690 --> 00:05:04.910
is our own Arab world
specialist, Dr. Muhannad Salhi.

00:05:04.910 --> 00:05:06.710
Thank you.

00:05:06.710 --> 00:05:13.200
[ Applause ]

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:14.540
&gt;&gt; Thank you Mary-Jane.

00:05:14.540 --> 00:05:15.840
Welcome everybody.

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:18.580
Thank you for joining us.

00:05:18.580 --> 00:05:23.710
Rana Al Kadi, a native of
Medina, began to carve her place

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:27.060
in the world of architecture
over 15 years ago,

00:05:27.060 --> 00:05:32.050
at a time when related
jobs for women were few

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:34.310
in the kingdom of Saudi Arabia.

00:05:34.310 --> 00:05:39.500 position:56%
In what Al Kadi describes as a major
turning point, she transitioned

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:43.100
from a career in petroleum
to pursue her passion

00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:45.500
for architectural design.

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:49.900
As she continued to gain
expertise in visual arts,

00:05:49.900 --> 00:05:54.390
as well as architectural planning
and interiors, Al Kadi served

00:05:54.390 --> 00:05:59.400
in the Saudi Ministry of
Foreign Affairs in Madrid, Spain.

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:05.410
While in Madrid, she earned her PhD
from the Universidad Polytechnica,

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:10.440
Madrid, in conservation,
and restoration

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:13.100
of architectural heritage,

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:17.190
with a focus on Islamic
architecture in the Muslim region.

00:06:17.190 --> 00:06:20.590
Al Kadi's travels throughout
Tunisia, Morocco,

00:06:20.590 --> 00:06:24.290
Turkey and Spain further
enriched her interactions

00:06:24.290 --> 00:06:26.960
with [inaudible] architectural
sites,

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:30.240
inspiring her to continue
preservation and restoration work

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:34.790
in Saudi Arabia, and her
beloved home city of Medina.

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:38.110
Her expertise in visual
arts, architectural planning,

00:06:38.110 --> 00:06:40.880
and interiors, and conservation,

00:06:40.880 --> 00:06:48.360
has made Al Kadi a trailblazer
among Saudi women in her field.

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:53.280
Dr. Al Kadi's research and current
work focuses on Islamic domes,

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:57.060
and crossed arches in the
[inaudible] region, and the origins

00:06:57.060 --> 00:07:01.170
of Islamic vaults, and
the arrival in Spain

00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:05.230
and preservation intervention
in Europe.

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:08.380
More recently, Al Kadi
has had exhibitions

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:13.240
and private preservations projects
in historical sites and districts.

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:17.470
Blending cultural heritage with
fresh technological elements

00:07:17.470 --> 00:07:20.160
in a perfect illustration
of her passion

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.790
for meeting traditional
architecture with the contemporary.

00:07:23.790 --> 00:07:28.270
Her work offers a fresh look at
Islamic architectural elements,

00:07:28.270 --> 00:07:32.580
the bridge geographical,
region and historical contacts.

